-d is the directory file is in, 
-u is unified 
-pn is the number of slashes to destroy
-f force, 
-R swap old and new  
-c context 
-B pref - prefix file name 
-e ed script 
-F n fuzz factor :) inc it +2
-l ignore whitespace 
-N ignore patches already applied
patch -d /dir/ -u < me.patch 
or
# dummy '-C'
cat me.patch | patch -u -C -p1

running patch again , it asks to unapply the patch
make sure to use /tools/ns/bin/patch [v=2.1]
